]]\n* [[Thandie Newton]]\n* [[John C. Reilly]]\n{{div col end}}\n\nElsewhere:\n\nIn [[San Francisco]], performer and activist [[Joan Baez]] serenaded the crowd with \"We Shall Overcome\" in Spanish.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bradshaw |first=Kate |title=Saturday: 'Community Action Rally' in Redwood City to follow Trump inauguration |newspaper=The Almanac |location=Menlo Park, California |date=January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.almanacnews.com/news/2017/01/19/saturday-local-community-action-rally-to-follow-trump-inauguration |accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Comedian [[Colin Mochrie]] and Actress [[Eliza Dushku]] attended [[Boston]]'s march.<ref name=DenofGeek/> Singer [[Carole King]] was among 30 residents rallying in [[Stanley, Idaho]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2017/1/22/14350808/womens-marches-largest-demonstration-us-history-map |title=The Women's Marches may have been the largest demonstration in US history |last=Frostenson |first=Sarah |date=January 22, 2017 |publisher=Vox|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref> Author [[Stephen King]] participated in a march in [[Sarasota, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Djinis |first1=Elizabeth |title=Thousands turn out for Sarasota Women's Solidarity March |url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20170121/thousands-turn-out-for-sarasota-womens-solidarity-march |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Singer [[Kacey Musgraves]]<ref name=Billboard/> and comedian [[Chris Rock]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lind |first1=J.R. |title=Nashville Women's March Draws 15K, Including Chris Rock and a Goat |url=http://patch.com/tennessee/nashville/nashville-womens-march-draws-15k-including-chris-rock-goat |publisher=Patch.com |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126205128/http://patch.com/tennessee/nashville/nashville-womens-march-draws-15k-including-chris-rock-goat |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref> were both present in [[Nashville]], Tennessee. [[Seth Rogen]] tweeted video from [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hauslohner |first1=Abigail |title='Squeezing into every street': Hundreds of thousands march across the country |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/01/21/womens-march-events-underway-across-the-country/ |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |date=January 21, 2017 |quote=Seth Rogan tweeted from the crowd in New Orleans |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124081024/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/01/21/womens-march-events-underway-across-the-country/ |archivedate=January 24, 2017 }}</ref> Actor [[Rami Malek]] was present in [[Paris, France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/celebrities-show-support-womens-marches-world/story?id=44948756 |title=Celebs Show Support for Women's Marches Around the World |author=Joi-Marie McKenzie |date=January 21, 2017 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=February 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203081350/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/celebrities-show-support-womens-marches-world/story?id=44948756 |archivedate=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Messaging and visual imagery ==\n=== Pussyhat Project ===\n\n{{Main|Pussyhat}}\n[[File:2017.01.20 Alaska Air Flight 6 in Pink LAX-DCA 00049 (31620242283).jpg|right|thumb|Sewn and knit [[pussyhat]]s being worn on a plane to Washington D.C.]]\n\nThe Pussyhat Project was a nationwide effort initiated by Krista Suh and Jayna Zweiman, a screenwriter and architect located in Los Angeles, to create [[pussyhat]]s, pink hats to be worn at the march for visual impact.<ref name=\"phourstory\">{{cite web |title=Our Story |url=https://www.pussyhatproject.com/our-story/ |publisher=Pussy Hat Project |accessdate=September 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923095849/https://www.pussyhatproject.com/our-story/ |archivedate=September 23, 2017 }}</ref> In response to this call, crafters all over the United States began making these hats using patterns provided on the project website for use with either a [[knitting]] method, [[crocheting]] and even [[sewing]] with fabrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pussyhatproject.com/ |title=Main website page |publisher=PussyHatProject.com|access-date=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124195827/https://www.pussyhatproject.com/ |archivedate=January 24, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=USA/> The project's goal was to have one million hats handed out at the Washington March.<ref name=USA>{{cite news |last1=Shamus |first1=Kristen Jordan |title=Pussyhat Project is sweeping nation ahead of the Women's March on Washington |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/01/14/pink-cat-ear-hats-sweeping-nation-ahead-womens-march/96584374/ |work=Detroit Free Press/USA Today |date=January 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114211559/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/01/14/pink-cat-ear-hats-sweeping-nation-ahead-womens-march/96584374/ |archivedate=January 14, 2017 }}</ref> The hats are made using pink yarns or fabrics and were originally designed to be a positive form of protest for Trump's inauguration by Krista Suh. Suh, from Los Angeles, wanted a hat for the cooler climate in Washington, D. C. and made herself a hat for the protest, realizing the potential: \"we could all wear them, make a unified statement\".<ref name=Kahn>{{cite news |last1=Kahn |first1=Mattie |title=The Pussyhat Is an Imperfect, Powerful Feminist Symbol That Thousands Will Be Wearing This Weekend in DC; The women behind the controversial cat-eared phenomenon explain their thinking. |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/news/a42152/pussyhat-project-knit-protest/ |work=Elle |date=January 17, 2017 |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |quote=Festooned in cat ears and crafted from hot pink yarn, the hats are the creation of Krista Suh and Jayna Zweiman, friends who wanted to come up with just one more way for women to announce their opposition to Donald Trump's election. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121001327/http://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/news/a42152/pussyhat-project-knit-protest/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref> One of the project founders, Jayna Zweiman, stated \"I think it's resonating a lot because we're really saying that no matter who you are or where you are, you can be politically active.\"<ref name= USA/> Suh and Zwieman worked with Kat Coyle, the owner of a local knitting supply shop called The Little Knittery, to come up with the original design. The project launched in November 2016 and quickly became popular on social media with over 100,000 downloads of the pattern to make the hat.<ref>{{cite news |last=Garfield |first=Leanna |date=January 18, 2017 |title=Thousands of women will wear pink 'pussy hats' the day after Trump's inauguration |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/pussy-hats-womens-march-washington-trump-inauguration-2017-1 |publisher=Businessinsider.com |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125222432/http://www.businessinsider.com/pussy-hats-womens-march-washington-trump-inauguration-2017-1 |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"phourstory\"/>\n\nThe name refers to the resemblance of the top corners of the hats to cat ears and attempts to [[Reappropriation|reclaim]] the derogatory term \"[[pussy]]\", a play on Trump's [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording|widely reported 2005 remarks]] that women would let him \"grab them by the pussy\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/pink-pussyhats-will-be-making-statement-womens-march-washington-1601088 |title=Pink 'pussyhats' will be making statement at the Women's March on Washington |last=Keating |first=Fiona |date=January 14, 2017 |newspaper=International Business Times UK |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115165657/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/pink-pussyhats-will-be-making-statement-womens-march-washington-1601088 |archivedate=January 15, 2017 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38666373 \"'Pussyhat' knitters join long tradition of crafty activism\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121141233/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38666373 |date=January 21, 2017 }} BBC News. January 19, 2017.</ref> Many of the hats worn by marchers in Washington, D.C., were created by crafters who were unable to attend and wished them to be worn by those who could, to represent their presence. Those hats optionally contained notes from the crafters to the wearers, expressing support. They were distributed by the crafters themselves, by yarn stores at the points of origin, carried to the event by marchers, and also distributed at the destination.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McGough |first1=Annelise |title=The Creators of the Pussyhat Project Explain How Craft Projects Are Protest |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3067204/innovation-agents/the-creators-of-the-pussy-hat-phenomenon-explain-how-craft-projects-are-pr |work=Fast Company |date=January 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120150425/https://www.fastcompany.com/3067204/innovation-agents/the-creators-of-the-pussy-hat-phenomenon-explain-how-craft-projects-are-pr |archivedate=January 20, 2017 }}</ref> The production of the hats caused reported shortages of pink knitting yarn across the United States.<ref>Ravani, Sarah (January 17, 2017). [http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Shortage-on-pink-yarn-doesn-t-stop-people-from-10863764.php \"'Pussyhat Project for Women's March causes run on pink yarn\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202002755/http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Shortage-on-pink-yarn-doesn-t-stop-people-from-10863764.php |date=February 2, 2017 }}, ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved January 18, 2017.</ref><ref>Brodeur, Nicole (January 10, 2017). [http://www.seattletimes.com/life/lifestyle/pussyhat-production-causes-run-on-pink-yarn/ \"Pussyhat production causes run on pink yarn\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224053825/http://www.seattletimes.com/life/lifestyle/pussyhat-production-causes-run-on-pink-yarn/ |date=February 24, 2017 }}, \"Seattle Times\".</ref><ref>WWMT Staff (January 13, 2017). [http://wwmt.com/news/nation-world/craft-stores-struggling-to-keep-pink-yarn-in-stock-ahead-of-washington-womens-march \"Craft stores struggling to keep pink yarn in stock ahead of Washington Women's March\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224054219/http://wwmt.com/news/nation-world/craft-stores-struggling-to-keep-pink-yarn-in-stock-ahead-of-washington-womens-march |date=February 24, 2017 }}, \"WWMT West Michigan\".</ref><ref>DeNardo, Mike (January 7, 2017 ). [http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/01/07/women-knit-hats-to-wear-to-washington-march-day-after-trump-inauguration/ \"Women to Don Knitted Pink \u201cPussyhats\u201d During Inauguration Weekend\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224133111/http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/01/07/women-knit-hats-to-wear-to-washington-march-day-after-trump-inauguration/ |date=February 24, 2017 }}, \"CBS Philly\".</ref> On the day of the march, [[NPR]] compared the hats to the \"[[Make America Great Again]]\" hats worn by Trump supporters, in that both represented groups that had at one point been politically marginalized; both sent \"simultaneously unifying and antagonistic\" messages; and both were simple in their messages.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kurtzleben |first1=Danielle |title=With 'Pussyhats,' Liberals Get Their Own Version of the Red Trucker Hat |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/01/21/510997192/with-pussyhats-liberals-get-their-own-version-of-the-red-trucker-hat |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122014229/http://www.npr.org/2017/01/21/510997192/with-pussyhats-liberals-get-their-own-version-of-the-red-trucker-hat |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> Pussyhats were featured later on the fashion [[fashion runway|runway]],<ref name=\"Pussyhat on the Runway\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/26/fashion/milan-fashion-week-versace-missoni-bottega-veneta.html?smid=tw-share&_r=0 |title=The Pussy Hat Comes to the Runway |last=Friedman |first=Vanessa |date=February 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801000703/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/26/fashion/milan-fashion-week-versace-missoni-bottega-veneta.html?smid=tw-share&_r=0 |archivedate=August 1, 2017 }}</ref> and on the covers of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and ''[[The New Yorker]]''.\n\n=== Signage ===\nIn [[Richmond, Virginia]], attendees of the March on Washington participated in an \"Art of Activism\" series of workshops at Studio Two Three, a printmaking studio for artists in [[Scott's Addition]].<ref name=\"Remmers\">{{cite news |last1=Remmers |first1=Vanessa |title=Local participants of Women's March on Washington descend on art studio to prepare |url=http://www.richmond.com/news/local/city-of-richmond/article_b01ebef8-bc30-58f4-9b97-230bfd78560f.html |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |date=January 18, 2017 |accessdate=January 20, 2017 |page=B1}}</ref>\n\nIn Los Angeles, actor Amir Talai was carrying the sign \"I'll see you nice white ladies at the next #blacklivesmatter march right?\" to express frustration at the lack of participation by white Americans in the Black Lives Matter movement, and simultaneously hopeful of encouraging them to do so. The photo of Talai with the sign went viral over the internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fusion.net/story/382776/amir-talai-viral-photo-womens-march-nice-white-ladies-black-lives-matter/ |title=An interview with the guy behind one of the most controversial signs from the Women's March |last=Meyerson |first=Collier |date=January 24, 2017 |publisher=Fusion |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125001852/http://fusion.net/story/382776/amir-talai-viral-photo-womens-march-nice-white-ladies-black-lives-matter/ |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]] acknowledged that it altered photographs of the Women's March on Washington, blurring the word ''Trump'' in a sign that reads, \"God Hates Trump\" and another that reads, \"Trump & GOP \u2014 Hands Off Women\" as well as other placards that referenced parts of a woman's anatomy. A spokesperson for the National Archives explained that the censorship was designed to avoid politicizing the event and to protect children and young people who might see the signs.<ref>[https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/478903-national-archives-says-it-altered-womens-march-photo-to-blur National Archives says it altered Trump signs, other messages in Women's March photo] BY TAL AXELROD, The Hill, 17 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n== Response ==\n=== Academics ===\nWhile the march aims to create a [[social movement]], Marcia Chatelain of [[Center for Social Justice Research, Teaching, & Service|Georgetown University's Center for Social Justice]] commented that its success will depend on the marchers' ability to maintain momentum in the following weeks. \"One of the goals of any type of march or any type of visible sign of solidarity is to get inspired, to inspire people to do more. And the question is, at the march, what kind of organizational structures or movements will also be present to help people know how to channel their energy for the next day and for the long haul?\"<ref name=\":0\"/> Historian [[Michael Kazin]] also commented on the importance of a long-term strategy: \"All successful movements in American history have both inside and outside strategy. If you're just protesting, and it just stops there, you're not going to get anything done.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/12/21/506299560/womens-march-on-washington-aims-to-be-more-than-protest-but-will-it |title=Organizers Hope Women's March on Washington Inspires, Evolves |date=December 21, 2016 |publisher=NPR |first=Alejandra Maria |last=Salazar |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122172615/http://www.npr.org/2016/12/21/506299560/womens-march-on-washington-aims-to-be-more-than-protest-but-will-it |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the protest, museum curators around the world sought to gather signs and other cultural artifacts of the marches.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Lisa |title=Museums Across the World Are Collecting Women's March Signs |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/museums-across-the-world-are-collecting-womens-march-signs.html |work=New York |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124071928/http://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/museums-across-the-world-are-collecting-womens-march-signs.html |archivedate=January 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Politicians ===\nMany members of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] announced that they would not attend Trump's inauguration ceremony, with the numbers growing after he made disparaging remarks about veteran House member and civil rights leader [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]]. Some of them said they would attend the Women's March.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/17/congress-members-not-going-to-trump-inauguration/96652942 |title=More than 60 Democrats are not attending the Trump inauguration |last1=Solis |first1=Steph |last2=Collins |first2=Eliza |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 17, 2017 |accessdate=January 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126121601/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/17/congress-members-not-going-to-trump-inauguration/96652942/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nMaine Representative [[Chellie Pingree]] said she would instead visit a Planned Parenthood center and a business owned by immigrants on Inauguration Day before going to Washington to appear on stage with other politicians who refused to attend. \"We need to do everything we can to let the incoming administration know we are not happy about their agenda. I've had unprecedented numbers of my constituents calling me worried about healthcare, the environment, public education, and they feel disrespected,\" she said.<ref name=\"The Guardian2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/20/womens-march-washington-donald-trump-protest |title=Women's March organizers prepare for hundreds of thousands of protesters |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Walters |first=Joanna |date=January 20, 2017|access-date=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123083309/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/20/womens-march-washington-donald-trump-protest |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2017, Trump wrote on his personal [[Twitter]] account: \"Watched protests yesterday but was under the impression that we just had an election! Why didn't these people vote? Celebs hurt cause badly.\" Two hours later, he sent a more placatory tweet: \"Peaceful protests are a hallmark of our democracy. Even if I don't always agree, I recognize the rights of people to express their views.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=David |title=Trump: Why didn't marchers vote? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/22/donald-trump-marchers-cia-tweets-inauguration/96919252 |work=USA Today |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122175202/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/22/donald-trump-marchers-cia-tweets-inauguration/96919252/ |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pengelly |first1=Martin |title=Donald Trump says controversial speech at CIA memorial was a 'win' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/22/donald-trump-cia-speech-win-twitter-protests |work=The Guardian |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122140457/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/22/donald-trump-cia-speech-win-twitter-protests |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> A White House official criticized the March for not welcoming [[United States pro-life movement|abortion rights opponents]], and then criticized [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s comment that she \"thought an awful lot about blowing up the White House\".<ref>{{cite news |title=White House Blasts Media, Madonna Over Women's Marches |url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/White-House-Attacks-Media-Madonna-in-First-Official-Response-to-Womens-Marches-411449395.html |publisher=NBC New York |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125051513/http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/White-House-Attacks-Media-Madonna-in-First-Official-Response-to-Womens-Marches-411449395.html |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSenator [[Bernie Sanders]], who attended the March in [[Montpelier, Vermont]], said Trump should listen to the protesters: \"Listen to the needs of women. Listen to the needs of the immigrant community. Listen to the needs of workers. Listen to what's going on with regards to climate change&nbsp;... Modify your positions. Let's work together to try to save this planet and protect the middle class.\"<ref name=\"Montpelier Bernie\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/2017/01/21/montpelier-womens-march-draws-7000/96888920 |title=Montpelier women's march draws 15,000 |newspaper=Burlington Free Press |author=D'Ambrosio, Dan |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |date=January 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bernie-sanders-president-trump-establishment-attacks-amusing/ |title=Bernie Sanders finds President Trump's 'establishment' attacks 'amusing' |work=[[Face the Nation]] |publisher=CBS News |first=Emily |last=Schultheis |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123081051/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bernie-sanders-president-trump-establishment-attacks-amusing/ |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Hillary Clinton]], the 2016 Democratic presidential candidate, offered her support on Twitter, calling the march \"awe-inspiring\" and stated \"[I] hope it brought joy to others as it did to me\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/22/politics/hillary-clinton-tweet-womens-march/index.html |title=Hillary Clinton tweets support for Women's March |first=Caroline |last=Kenny |publisher=CNN |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123020608/http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/22/politics/hillary-clinton-tweet-womens-march/index.html |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing a tweet that offended other lawmakers and the public, [[Bill Kintner]] resigned from his position as Nebraska State Senator.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/nebraska-lawmaker-bill-kintner-resigns-over-womens-march-tweet.html |title=Nebraska State Senator Resigns After Offensive Women's March Tweet |author=Gabriella Paiella |date=January 26, 2017 |website=New York |accessdate=January 26, 2017 |quote=Kintner retweeted a now-deleted tweet by Larry Elder, a conservative radio host. In it, three women are pictured holding signs referencing Donald Trump's 'grab them by the pussy' comments; Elder's comment was 'Ladies, I think you're safe.' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125210023/http://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/nebraska-lawmaker-bill-kintner-resigns-over-womens-march-tweet.html |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nJohn Carman, a Republican official in South Jersey mocked the Women's March, asking if the protest&nbsp;would \"be over in time for them to cook dinner\". He lost the next election on November 7, 2017, against a political newcomer, Ashley Bennett.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sasko|first1=Claire|title=South Jersey official who mocked D.C. Women's march defeated by a woman|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2017/11/08/ashley-bennett-john-carman-south-jersey/|accessdate=January 19, 2018|work=Philly Magazine|publisher=Metro Corp.|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]], which is associated with the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]], had planned to give their human rights award to the 2017 Women's March. After a German Jewish organization, however, protested in an open letter,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jfda.de/blog/2018/11/06/offener-brief-gegen-die-menschenrechtspreis-fes-womens-march-usa/|title=Offener Brief gegen die Verleihung des Menschenrechtspreises der FES an den Women's March USA {{!}} JFDA|date=2018-11-06|work=JFDA|access-date=2018-11-08|language=de-DE}}</ref> accusing the organizers of antisemitic statements and ties to antisemites, the foundation put the award on ice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.n-tv.de/politik/Kein-Preis-fuer-den-Women-s-March-article20710578.html|title=Kein Preis f\u00fcr den Women's March|last=Nachrichten|first=n-tv|work=n-tv.de|access-date=2018-11-08|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/article/view/id/33238|title=Women's March USA : \"Offener Antisemitismus\" {{!}} J\u00fcdische Allgemeine|last=K.d.\u00f6.R.|first=Zentralrat der Juden in Deutschland|website=www.juedische-allgemeine.de|language=en|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Celebrities ===\nApart from the celebrities present at the march, others such as [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]] made statements of support for it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/karenhua/2017/01/18/the-celebrities-attending-the-womens-march-on-washington/ |title=The Celebrities Attending The Women's March on Washington |last=Hua |first=Karen |newspaper=Forbes|access-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204172148/http://www.forbes.com/sites/karenhua/2017/01/18/the-celebrities-attending-the-womens-march-on-washington/#1828e3cd5881 |archivedate=February 4, 2017 }}</ref> The latter, who endorsed Hillary Clinton and is a friend to [[Barack Obama]], gave a speech during a concert in Australia, saying, \"[[The E Street Band]] is glad to be here in [[Western Australia]]. But we're a long way from home, and our hearts and spirits are with the hundreds of thousands of women and men that marched yesterday in every city in America and in [[Melbourne]] who rallied against hate and division and in support of tolerance, inclusion, reproductive rights, civil rights, racial justice, LGBTQ rights, the environment, wage equality, gender equality, healthcare, and immigrant rights. We stand with you. We are the new American resistance.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brucespringsteen.net/news/2017/we-are-the-new-american-resistance |title=We are the new American resistance. |publisher=Brucespringsteen.net |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125165546/http://brucespringsteen.net/news/2017/we-are-the-new-american-resistance |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/springsteen-on-womens-march-the-new-american-resistance-w462367 |title=Bruce Springsteen on Women's March: 'The New American Resistance' |date=January 22, 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123074732/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/springsteen-on-womens-march-the-new-american-resistance-w462367 |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Cyndi Lauper]] commented on Madonna's controversial speech at the Washington march, saying, \"Anger is not better than clarity and humanity. That is what opens people's minds. When you want to change people's mind, you have to share your real story.\"<ref name=\"The Wrap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/cyndi-lauper-doesnt-think-madonnas-womens-march-speech-served-purpose-video |title=Cyndi Lauper Doesn't Think Madonna's Women's March Speech 'Served Our Purpose' |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |date=January 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126174112/http://www.thewrap.com/cyndi-lauper-doesnt-think-madonnas-womens-march-speech-served-purpose-video/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Jon Voight]] called the march \"destructive\" and said it was \"against the president and against the government\". He was particularly critical of [[Shia LaBeouf]] and march participant [[Miley Cyrus]], saying \"they have a lot of followers\" and felt their stances were \"teaching treason\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rare.us/rare-people/jon-voight-ripped-into-the-womens-march-and-two-big-name-stars-who-have-been-opposing-president-trump/ |title=Jon Voight ripped into the Women's March and two big name stars who oppose President Trump |date=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324053821/http://rare.us/rare-people/jon-voight-ripped-into-the-womens-march-and-two-big-name-stars-who-have-been-opposing-president-trump/ |archivedate=March 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Piers Morgan]], a friend of Trump's, stated the march was a reaction by women that \"a man won\" and that \"At its core, it was about Trump-hating and resentment that he won and Hillary lost\". He also felt that it was democratic to protest, but not due to the result of a democratic election. In response to Morgan's comments about the march, [[Ewan McGregor]] canceled his appearance on ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'', which Morgan was hosting.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.harpersbazaar.co.uk/culture/culture-news/news/a39525/ewan-mcgregor-cancels-good-morning-britain-interview/ |title=Ewan McGregor cancels interview after Piers Morgan's Women's March comments |last=Alexander |first=Ella |work=Harper's Bazaar.co.uk |date=January 24, 2017|access-date=May 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Follow-up ==\n{{See also|2018 Women's March|2019 Women's March|2020 Women's March}}\n\nFollowing the march, the organizers of the Women's March on Washington posted the \"10 Actions for the first 100 Days\" campaign to keep up the momentum from the march.<ref name=\"DFP 10 actions\">{{cite news |url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/2017/01/22/10-actions-womens-march/96935642 |title=Women's March launches 10 actions for first 100 days |last=Jordan |first=Kristen Shamus |date=January 22, 2017 |website=The Detroit Free Press |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125160453/http://www.freep.com/story/news/2017/01/22/10-actions-womens-march/96935642/ |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref> The first action included contacting senators about concerns, with an option of using \"Hear Our Voice\" postcards.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/100 |title=10 Actions/100 Days |website=Women's March on Washington |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125015019/https://www.womensmarch.com/100 |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref> A new action was provided every 10 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.krcrtv.com/north-coast-news/womens-march-10-actions-in-100-days/288615795 |title=Women's March: Participants to take '10 Actions in 100 Days' |last=Javid |first=Nazy |date=January 25, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202042659/http://www.krcrtv.com/north-coast-news/womens-march-10-actions-in-100-days/288615795 |archivedate=February 2, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nFilmmaker [[Michael Moore]] called for 100 days of resistance, for Trump's first 100 days of his presidency.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2017/01/09/watch-michael-moore-calls-for-100-days-of-resistance-starting-with-trumps-inauguration/ |title=WATCH: Michael Moore calls for \"100 days of resistance\" starting with Donald Trump's inauguration |last=Rozsa |first=Matthew |date=January 9, 2017 |website=Salon |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120111120/http://www.salon.com/2017/01/09/watch-michael-moore-calls-for-100-days-of-resistance-starting-with-trumps-inauguration/ |archivedate=January 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, the Women's March official Twitter feed celebrated the birthday of [[Assata Shakur]], an African-American on the FBI most wanted terrorists list who was convicted of murder, leading to criticism from conservative media outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/05/07/181914429/fbi-most-wanted-terrorists-list-who-is-assata-shakur|title=FBI Most Wanted Terrorists List: Who Is Assata Shakur?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Assata Shakur birthday honored by Women's March organizers |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/07/18/assata-shakur-birthday-honored-by-womens-march-organizers.html |publisher=Fox News |date=July 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730074103/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/07/18/assata-shakur-birthday-honored-by-womens-march-organizers.html |archivedate=July 30, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=When the 'Resistance' Gets Reprehensible |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/449570/when-resistance-gets-reprehensible |work=National Review |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015120609/http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/449570/when-resistance-gets-reprehensible |archivedate=October 15, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Lampen |first=Claire |url=https://mic.com/articles/182595/six-months-after-the-womens-march-on-washington-the-resistance-revival-has-a-message-for-trump |title=Six months after the Women's March on Washington, the Resistance Revival has a message for Trump |work=Mic |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref> In an August 1, 2017, editorial, [[Bari Weiss]] criticized three co-chairs for their association with [[Louis Farrakhan]], and for failing to reject anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/01/opinion/womens-march-progressives-hate.html|title=Opinion: When Progressives Embrace Hate|last=Weiss|first=Bari|date=July 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> In a reply letter, co-Chair Bob Bland dismissed critics as \"apologists for the status quo, racist ideology and the white nationalist patriarchy\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bland |first1=Bob |title=Letter to the editor: From a Women's March Leader: 'We Need to Stand United' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/03/opinion/from-a-womens-march-leader-we-need-to-stand-united.html |accessdate=September 17, 2017 |work=The New York Times |date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917213625/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/03/opinion/from-a-womens-march-leader-we-need-to-stand-united.html |archivedate=September 17, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, leaders of the decentralized Women's Marches across the country formed a new organization, [[March On (organization)|March On]], and launched a Super PAC called March On's Fight Back PAC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-score/2017/10/19/close-virginia-governor-polls-set-democratic-nerves-on-edge-222885|title=Close Virginia governor polls set Democratic nerves on edge|website=POLITICO|access-date=November 17, 2017}}</ref> Led by [[Vanessa Wruble]], one of the co-founders and chief architects of the Women's March on Washington, March On announced the goal of creating political change through their \"March on the Polls\" campaign, including marching people to voting booths for the November 2018 midterms for a \"March on the Midterms\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/march-on-impeach-trump-vanessa-wruble|title=This Holiday Season, Give the Gift of Impeachment|work=Vogue|access-date=November 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref> \"March on aims to coordinate actions at the federal, state, and local level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.facebook.com/wearemarchon/videos/743846059137766/|title=March on discussed on MSNBC|last=Thornell|first=Doug|date=November 9, 2017|work=MSNBC}}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2018, a second [[2018 Women's March|Women's March]] was held, taking place in cities around the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/20/us/womens-march.html|title=Women's March 2018: Thousands of Protesters Take to the Streets|last=Tiefenth\u00e4ler|first=Ainara|date=January 20, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42767434|title=Women's March: What's changed one year on?|last=Wright|first=Katie|date=January 21, 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> Demonstrations were also held in [[2019 Women's March|2019]] and [[2020 Women's March|2020]].\n\n== Locations ==\n{{Main|List of 2017 Women's March locations}}\n<!--Please add only text with sources in this section.-->\nThe 2017 Women's Marches took place in many cities around the world since January 21, 2017.\n\n<!--Please only add images with iconic landmarks to the gallery - random crowd or individual pictures could have been taken anywhere and are repetitive.-->\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150\">\nFile:Womens-march-07881 (32298946482).jpg|[[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/police-estimate-000-atlanta-for-the-social-justice-march-the-capitol/PlaULPX2mykkjcHk799zLP|title=Police estimate: 60,000 in Atlanta for the social justice march to the Capitol|last=Torres|first=Kristina|date=January 21, 2017|website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=January 26, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125120023/http://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/police-estimate-000-atlanta-for-the-social-justice-march-the-capitol/PlaULPX2mykkjcHk799zLP/|archivedate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\nFile:Boston Womens March 2017.jpg|[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\nFile:Women's March, January 21 2017, Chicago (32066902410).jpg|[[Chicago, Illinois]]\nFile:London D7K 7598 (1) (31657365883).jpg|[[London, England]]\nFile:Women's March Los Angeles, Januat 21, 2017.jpg|[[Los Angeles, California]]\nFile:01-21-2017 - Women's March on NYC (10701).jpg|[[New York City, New York]]\nFile:2017.01.21 womensmarchparis 02.jpg|[[Paris, France]]\nFile:Womans March Roanoke Virginia.jpg|[[Roanoke, Virginia]]\nFile:Women's March 2017-01 (12).jpg|[[Washington, D.C.]]\nFile:Womens March Auckland 2017 Queen St.jpg|[[Auckland, New Zealand]]\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{external media|width=210px|align=right|headerimage=|video1=[https://www.c-span.org/video/?422332-1/womens-march-washington-protests-new-trump-administration \"Women's March on Washington\", January 21, 2017], [[C-SPAN]]<ref name=\"cspan\">{{Cite news |title=Women's March on Washington |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] |date=January 21, 2017 |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?422332-1/womens-march-washington-protests-new-trump-administration |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126010111/https://www.c-span.org/video/?422332-1%2Fwomens-march-washington-protests-new-trump-administration |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>}}\n* \"[[Tiny Hands]]\", a song released by [[Fiona Apple]] for the march\n* [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape|Donald Trump ''Access Hollywood'' tape]]\n* [[Women's Sunday]], 1908 women's march in London, England to rally for suffrage\n* [[Woman suffrage parade of 1913]] in Washington D.C. led by [[Alice Paul]], to rally for suffrage\n* [[Women's March (South Africa)]], to protest the introduction of the Apartheid pass laws in Pretoria, August 9, 1956\n* [[Million Woman March]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, October 25, 1997\n* [[List of protest marches on Washington, D.C.]]\n*[https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/1536/collection_organization# The Why Are You Marching? project], archived at Smith College's [https://libraries.smith.edu/special-collections/about/sophia-smith-collection-womens-history Sophia Smith Collection of Women's History]\n\n{{Portal bar|Feminism|Politics|Society|United States}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite news |last=Wolf |first=Z. Byron |title=Comparing Trump's inauguration crowd to the Women's March |publisher=CNN |date=January 21, 2017 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/21/politics/womens-march-donald-trump-inauguration-sizes/index.html |ref=harv |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}\n* {{Cite news |last=Bosman |first=Julie |title=In a Rust Belt Town, the Women's March Draws Shrugs and Cheers From Afar |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 21, 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/niles-michigan-trump-no-women-march.html |ref=harv |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{attached KML|from=List of 2017 Women's March locations|display=inline,title}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|2017 Women's March}}\n* {{official website}}\n*[https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c89029hh/ Finding Aid to one of the largest collections of ephemera and posters from marches across California at the Sutro Library San Francisco, CA]\n\n{{Women's March}}\n{{Protests against Trump footer}}\n{{Trump presidency}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Women's March, 2017}}\n[[Category:2017 in American politics]]\n[[Category:2017 in Asia]]\n[[Category:2017 in Europe]]\n[[Category:2017 in North America]]\n[[Category:2017 in Oceania]]\n[[Category:2017 in Africa]]\n[[Category:2017 protests]]\n[[Category:2017 in women's history|March]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the United States]]\n[[Category:Fourth-wave feminism]]\n[[Category:History of women's rights]]\n[[Category:Inauguration of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:January 2017 events]]\n[[Category:Protests against Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Reactions to the election of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Women's marches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women's March|2017 Women's March]]\n[[Category:Gatherings of women]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the movement as a whole|an individual listing of protests|List of 2017 Women's March locations}}\n{{short description|Worldwide political rallies for women's rights}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title          = 2017 Women's March<br/>Women's March on Washington\n| side3          = \n| partof         = the [[Women's rights movement]] and [[Protests against Donald Trump]]\n| image          = Women's March on Washington (32593123745).jpg\n| caption        = Demonstrators at the Women's March on Washington in Washington, D.C.\n| date           = January 21\u201322, 2017\n| place          = Worldwide, with flagship march in Washington, D.C.\n| causes         = {{plain list|\n* Opposition to the deportment and political positions of President [[Donald Trump]] and his [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|administration]]<ref name=\"Cauterucci\"/><ref name=Guiding/>}}\n| goals=\"Protection of our rights, our safety, our health, and our families \u2013 recognizing that our vibrant and diverse communities are the strength of our country\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/womens-march/story?id=44884784 |title=Everything You Need to Know About the Women's March |first1=Meridith |last1=McGraw |first2=Adam |last2=Kelsey |date=January 20, 2017 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122022239/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/womens-march/story?id=44884784 |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n{{plain list|\n* [[Women's right]], [[LGBTQ rights]], [[gender equality]], [[racial equality]], [[worker rights]], [[disability rights]]\n* [[Immigration reform]], [[Health care reform]], [[Freedom of religion]], [[Environmental protection]]\n}}\n| methods        = [[Protest march]]\n| status         = \n| result         = \n| side1          = \n| side2          = \n| leadfigures1   = Co-founders:{{plain list|\n* [[Teresa Shook]]<ref name=\"Hawaii News Now\" />\n* [[Vanessa Wruble]]<ref name=\"Vogue-Felsenthal\"/>\n* Evvie Harmon\n* Bob Bland<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Stein\"/>\n}}\n| leadfigures2   = Co-chairs:{{plain list|\n* [[Linda Sarsour]]\n* [[Tamika Mallory]]\n* [[Carmen Perez]]\n* [[Bob Bland]]<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Stein\"/>\n}}\n| leadfigures3   = Honorary co-chairs:{{plain list|\n* [[Gloria Steinem]]\n* [[Harry Belafonte]]\n* [[LaDonna Harris]]\n* [[Angela Davis]]\n* [[Dolores Huerta]]<ref name=\"USA TODAY\"/>\n}}\n| howmany1       = \n| howmany2       = \n| howmany3       = Estimated over 200,000 people in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Chenoweth\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/02/07/this-is-what-we-learned-by-counting-the-womens-marches/|title=Analysis {{!}} This is what we learned by counting the women's marches|last=Chenoweth|first=Erica|date=February 7, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 23, 2018|last2=Pressman|first2=Jeremy|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In Washington, D.C., it was the largest protest since the anti-Vietnam War protests in the 1960s and 1970s outside of the annual March for Life<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/March_for_Life_(Washington,_D.C.)#Attendance</ref> in Washington D. C.\nEstimated 3,300,000\u20135,600,000 in the United States<ref name=\"Atlantic exhausting work\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/01/womens-march-protest-count/514166 |title=The Exhausting Work of Tallying America's Largest Protest |last1=Waddell |first1=Kavel |work=[[The Atlantic]] |edition=online |date=January 23, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126005341/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/01/womens-march-protest-count/514166/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"Chenoweth\" /> Estimated up to 5 million worldwide<ref name=\"auto27\"/><ref name=\"auto8\" />\n| casualties1     = \n| casualties2     = \n| casualties3     = \n| injuries        = \n| fatalities      = \n| arrests         = \n| detentions      = \n| charged         = \n| fined           = \n| notes           = Official websites:<br/>{{url|https://www.womensmarch.com|WomensMarch.com}}<br/>{{url|https://www.pussyhatproject.com/}}{{paragraph break}}\n| sidebox         = \n}}\n{{Wikinews|Women's March becomes largest single day protest in Modern U.S. history}}\nThe '''Women's March'''<!--DO NOT ADD 2017 TO BOLDED TEXT; IT IS MENTIONED LATER IN SENTENCE.--><ref name=\"FT 100,000\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7b34cd82-dfe2-11e6-8405-9e5580d6e5fb |title=Trump reacts to mass protests with conciliatory tweet: More than 2.5m people gather around the world to take part in Women's March |date=January 22, 2017 |work=Financial Times |last2=Rennison |first2=Joe |last3=Whipp |first3=Lindsay |last4=Bullock |first4=Nicole|access-date=January 22, 2017 |last1=Weaver |first1=Courtney |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122050503/https://www.ft.com/content/7b34cd82-dfe2-11e6-8405-9e5580d6e5fb |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=CNN-Ahuja01a>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/01/21/politics/womens-march-antarctica/index.html |title=Yes, even people in Antarctica are joining the Women's March movement |author=Masuma Ahuja |publisher=CNN |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123212039/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/01/21/politics/womens-march-antarctica/index.html |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=ForeignPolicy-TamkinGramer01a>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/01/21/the-womens-march-heard-round-the-world |title=The Women's March Heard Round the World |author1=Emily Tamkin |author2=Robbie Gramer |work=Foreign Policy |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |quote=The Women's March on Saturday ... grew into a day long international event both in support of women and in opposition to the president's past rhetoric and potential future policies. There were more than 600 events in 60 countries around the world, with millions taking to the streets. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126083204/http://foreignpolicy.com/2017/01/21/the-womens-march-heard-round-the-world/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>{{efn|It has also been called the Women's March Movement,<ref name=ABC-FCN-StephanieKim01a>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/womens-march-makes-its-way-to-the-first-coast/389706372 |title=Women's March makes its way to the First Coast |author=Stephanie Kim |publisher=ABC \u2013 First Coast News |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |quote=The Women's March Movement is going worldwide with 670 sister marches planned.}}</ref> or the Women's Marches,<ref name=USAToday01a>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/21/womens-march-aims-start-movement-trump-inauguration/96864158 |title=At 2.6&nbsp;million strong, Women's Marches crush expectations |last1=Przybyla |first1=Heidi M. |last2=Schouten |first2=Fredreka |work=[[USA Today]] |edition=online |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122002531/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/21/womens-march-aims-start-movement-trump-inauguration/96864158/ |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> or the Women's March on Washington and its sister Marches<ref name=\"auto27\"/> or solidarity marches<ref>{{cite news |last1=Upadhye |first1=Neeti |title=Women March Around the U.S. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/us/politics/100000004886060/women-march-around-the-us.html |website=The New York Times |date=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126064222/https://www.nytimes.com/video/us/politics/100000004886060/women-march-around-the-us.html |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>}} was a worldwide protest on January 21, 2017, the day after [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|the inauguration]] of President [[Donald Trump]]. Tensions rose due to his statements, considered by many as [[anti-women]] or otherwise offensive.<ref name=\"FT 100,000\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-women-idUSKBN1550DW |title=In challenge to Trump, women protesters swarm streets across U.S. |date=January 22, 2017 |agency=Reuters |last1=Malone |first1=Scott |last2=Gibson |first2=Ginger|access-date=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122000623/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-women-idUSKBN1550DW |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/866981483]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/866048551]] cite #20 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> It was [[March for Life (Washington, D.C.)|one of the largest]] single-day protests in U.S. history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/womens-march-anti-donald-trump-womens-rights-largest-protest-demonstration-us-history-political-a7541081.html|title=Women's March against Donald Trump is the largest day of protests in US history, say political scientists|last=Broomfield|first=Matt|newspaper=Independent|accessdate=January 25, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125182025/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/womens-march-anti-donald-trump-womens-rights-largest-protest-demonstration-us-history-political-a7541081.html|archivedate=January 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The goal of the annual marches is to advocate legislation and policies regarding human rights and other issues, including [[women's rights]], immigration reform, healthcare reform, [[reproductive rights]], the environment, [[LGBTQ]] rights, [[racial equality]], freedom of religion,<ref name=\"marchmission\">{{cite web |title=Mission and Vision |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/mission |publisher=Womensmarch.com |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125034852/https://www.womensmarch.com/mission/ |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref> workers' rights and tolerance. According to organizers, the goal was to \"send a bold message to our new administration on their first day in office, and to the world that [[women's rights are human rights]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/12/21/506299560/womens-march-on-washington-aims-to-be-more-than-protest-but-will-it|title=Organizers Hope Women's March on Washington Inspires, Evolves|last=Salazar|first=Alejandra Maria|date=December 21, 2016|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe main protest was in [[Washington, D.C.]], and is known as the '''Women's March on Washington'''<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/jia-tolentino/the-somehow-controversial-womens-march-on-washington |title=The Somehow Controversial Women's March on Washington |last=Tolentino |first=Jia |date=January 18, 2017 |work=The New Yorker|access-date=January 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120032957/http://www.newyorker.com/culture/jia-tolentino/the-somehow-controversial-womens-march-on-washington |archivedate=January 20, 2017 }}</ref> with many other marches taking place worldwide. The Washington March was streamed live on [[YouTube]], [[Facebook]], and [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/ |title=Women's March on Washington |quote=You can view the program live on a number of Jumbotrons on Independence Ave. and through all of our social media platforms, Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube |publisher=Women's March on Washington |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121005304/https://www.womensmarch.com/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref> The Washington March drew over 470,000 people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/22/us/politics/womens-march-trump-crowd-estimates.html|title=Analysis {{!}} Crowd Scientists Say Women\u2019s March in Washington Had 3 Times as Many People as Trump\u2019s Inauguration|last1=Wallace|first1=Tim|last2=Parlapiano|first2=Alicia|date=22 January 2017|work=New York Times||language=en-US}}</ref> Between 3,267,134 and 5,246,670 people participated in the marches in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/02/07/this-is-what-we-learned-by-counting-the-womens-marches/|title=This is what we learned by counting the women's marches}}</ref> approximately 1.0 to 1.6 percent of the U.S. population. Worldwide participation has been estimated at over seven million.<ref name=\"auto27\" /><ref name=\"auto8\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/womens-march.html |title='We're Not Going Away': Huge Crowds for Women's Marches Against Trump |last=Alcindor |first=Anemona Hartocollis, Yamiche |date=January 21, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=January 21, 2017 |last2=Chokshi |first2=Niraj |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121114906/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/womens-march.html |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/21/womens-march-aims-start-movement-trump-inauguration/96864158 |title=At 2.5&nbsp;million strong, Women's Marches crush expectations |date=January 21, 2017 |work=USA Today |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121233003/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/21/womens-march-aims-start-movement-trump-inauguration/96864158/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref> At least 408 marches were reported to have been planned in the U.S. and 168 in 81<ref name=\"auto27\" /> other countries.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{citation |last=Schmidt |first=Kierstein |title=Where Women's Marches Are |date=January 20, 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/17/us/womens-march.html |last2=Almukhtar |first2=Sarah |newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121084623/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/17/us/womens-march.html |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref> After the marches, organizers reported that around 673 marches took place worldwide, on all seven continents, 29 in Canada, 20 in Mexico,<ref name=\"FT 100,000\" /> and 1 in [[Antarctica]].<ref name=\"usatoday-7continents\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/21/womens-march-on-washington-antarctica/96882184/|access-date=January 25, 2017 |date=January 21, 2017 |title=There's even a Women's March in Antarctica |work=[[USA Today]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124200140/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/01/21/womens-march-on-washington-antarctica/96882184/ |archivedate=January 24, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://grist.org/opinion/womens-marches-occurring-across-seven-continents-include-a-focus-on-environment/ |title=Women's marches, occurring across seven continents, include a focus on environment |date=January 19, 2017 |work=Grist|access-date=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426152512/http://grist.org/opinion/womens-marches-occurring-across-seven-continents-include-a-focus-on-environment/ |archivedate=April 26, 2017 }}</ref> The crowds were peaceful: no arrests were made in D.C., Chicago, Los Angeles,{{efn|According to organizers, 750,000 people marched in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shaded pink, women's protest fills the streets of downtown L.A. |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-la-ln-womens-march-20170121-story.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126235231/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-la-ln-womens-march-20170121-story.html |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref>}} New York City, or Seattle, where a combined total of about two million people marched.<ref name=\"Zero Arrests\">{{cite news |url=http://www.citylab.com/politics/2017/01/no-arrests-at-womens-march-in-dc-los-angeles-new-york-chicago-austin-seattle/514067/ |title=Millions of Marchers, Zero Arrests |website=Citylab |last=Capps |first=Kriston |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123055400/http://www.citylab.com/politics/2017/01/no-arrests-at-womens-march-in-dc-los-angeles-new-york-chicago-austin-seattle/514067/ |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref> The organization's website states that they wanted to adhere to \"the nonviolent ideology of the Civil Rights movement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.womensmarch.com/march/|title=The March: Jan 21 2017|website=Women's March|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120055221/https://www.womensmarch.com/march/|archive-date=November 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Following the march, the organizers of the Women's March on Washington posted the \"10 Actions for the first 100 Days\" campaign for joint activism to keep up momentum from the march.<ref name=\"DFP 10 actions\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/100/ |title=10 Actions / 100 Days |website=Women's March on Washington|access-date=January 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131031403/https://www.womensmarch.com/100 |archivedate=January 31, 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:Sign Women's March.jpg|thumb|2017 Women's March in downtown, Los Angeles. ]]\n\n== Background ==\n=== Organizers ===\n[[File:Women&#039;s March on Washington 2017.jpg|thumb|Poster created by the official Women's March on Washington organizers]]\nOn November 9, 2016, the first day after [[Donald Trump]] was elected [[President of the United States]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Novick |first1=Ilana |title=March on Washington and beyond: How women are resisting Donald Trump |url=http://www.salon.com/2017/01/02/march-on-washington-and-beyond-how-women-are-resisting-donald-trump_partner |work=Salon |date=January 2, 2017 |accessdate=January 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103172050/http://www.salon.com/2017/01/02/march-on-washington-and-beyond-how-women-are-resisting-donald-trump_partner/ |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}</ref> in reaction to Trump's election campaign and political views,{{efn|\"Born of one woman's invitation to forty friends, the event is meant as a rejoinder to the fact that a candidate with a troubling history regarding women's rights\u2014one who actually bragged about committing sexual assault\u2014has made it to the White House.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Cobb, Jelani |title=The Return of Civil Disobedience |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/09/the-return-of-civil-disobedience |work=The New Yorker |date=January 9, 2017|access-date=January 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103051017/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/09/the-return-of-civil-disobedience |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}; and \"bragged about sexual assault,\" see, e.g., [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording]].</ref>}}<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/story/womens-march-on-washington-activists-organizers |title=The Women of the Women's March: Meet the Activists Who Are Planning One of the Largest Demonstrations in American History |magazine=W Magazine |date=January 19, 2017 |first1=Katherine |last1=Cusumano |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121062541/http://www.wmagazine.com/story/womens-march-on-washington-activists-organizers |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref> and to his defeat of presidential nominee [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Teresa Shook]] of [[Hawaii]] created a [[Facebook]] event and invited friends to march on Washington in protest.<ref name=\"Hawaii News Now\">{{cite news |title=Maui woman starts what could be largest Trump inauguration movement |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/34198283/maui-woman-starts-what-could-be-largest-trump-inauguration-movement |accessdate=September 4, 2017 |work=Hawaii News Now |date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905001441/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/34198283/maui-woman-starts-what-could-be-largest-trump-inauguration-movement |archivedate=September 5, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hana woman who created march feels elated, joyful but not famous |url=http://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2017/01/hana-woman-who-created-march-feels-elated-joyful-but-not-famous/ |accessdate=September 4, 2017 |work=The Maui News |date=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904205624/http://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2017/01/hana-woman-who-created-march-feels-elated-joyful-but-not-famous/ |archivedate=September 4, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=Perry |title=The woman who started the Women's March with a Facebook post reflects: 'It was mind-boggling' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2017/01/31/the-woman-who-started-the-womens-march-with-a-facebook-post-reflects-it-was-mind-boggling/ |accessdate=September 4, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |date=January 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908021325/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2017/01/31/the-woman-who-started-the-womens-march-with-a-facebook-post-reflects-it-was-mind-boggling/ |archivedate=September 8, 2017 }}</ref> Similar Facebook pages created by Evvie Harmon, Fontaine Pearson, [[Bob Bland]] (a New York fashion designer), Breanne Butler, and others quickly led to thousands of women signing up to march.<ref name=\"WMOW Explained\" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Kearney, Laila |title=Hawaii grandma's plea launches women's march in Washington |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-women-idUSKBN13U0GW |agency=Reuters |date=December 5, 2016 |accessdate=December 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230160815/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-women-idUSKBN13U0GW |archivedate=December 30, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Wulfhorst, Ellen |title=Trump Inauguration To Be Met By Mass 'Women's March on Washington' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-million-women-march_us_582642efe4b0c4b63b0cbfa5/ |work=HuffPost |date=November 11, 2016|access-date=December 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106212940/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-million-women-march_us_582642efe4b0c4b63b0cbfa5 |archivedate=January 6, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Cauterucci, Christina |title=Getting the Women's March on Washington on the Road |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/doublex/2016/11/the_women_s_march_on_washington_faces_uncertain_logistics_on_inauguration.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=November 23, 2016|access-date=December 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229122606/http://www.slate.com/articles/life/doublex/2016/11/the_women_s_march_on_washington_faces_uncertain_logistics_on_inauguration.html |archivedate=December 29, 2016 }}</ref> Harmon, Pearson, and Butler decided to unite their efforts and consolidate their pages, beginning the official Women's March on Washington.<ref name=\"WMOW Explained\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article116642998.html |title=Explaining the Women's March on Washington |publisher=McClatchyDC |date=November 23, 2017 |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202012006/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article116642998.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 }}</ref> To ensure that the march was led by women of differing races and backgrounds, [[Vanessa Wruble]], co-founder, and co-president of Okayafrica, served as Head of Campaign Operations and brought on Tamika D. Mallory, Carmen Perez and [[Linda Sarsour]] to serve as National Co-Chairs alongside Bland.<ref name=\"WMOW Explained\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/team/ |title=National Committee |publisher=Women's March on Washington|access-date=January 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101162318/https://www.womensmarch.com/team/ |archivedate=January 1, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"Vogue-Felsenthal\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/march-on-impeach-trump-vanessa-wruble|title=This Holiday Season, Give the Gift of Impeachment|last=Julia|first=Felsenthal|work=Vogue|access-date=March 26, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Former [[Miss New Jersey USA]] [[Janaye Ingram]] served as Head of Logistics.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/01/23/511267131/womens-march-organizer-we-are-committed-to-fighting-for-change |title=Women's March Organizer: 'We Are Committed' To Fighting For Change |date=January 23, 2017 |publisher=NPR |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126013916/http://www.npr.org/2017/01/23/511267131/womens-march-organizer-we-are-committed-to-fighting-for-change |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref> Filmmaker Paola Mendoza served as Artistic Director and a National Organizer.<ref name=\"vogueprofile\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Molina |first1=Mary Angelica |title=Meet Two of the Latina Organizers Leading the Women's March on Washington |url=http://remezcla.com/features/culture/latina-organizers-womens-march-on-washington/ |accessdate=October 7, 2017 |publisher=Remezcla.com |date=January 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007220104/http://remezcla.com/features/culture/latina-organizers-womens-march-on-washington/ |archivedate=October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nDuring \"the first hours of the first meeting for what would become the Women's March,\" Mallory and Perez allegedly put forward a [[Jewish views on slavery#Assessing the extent of Jewish involvement in the Atlantic slave trade|debunked antisemitic conspiracy theory regarding Jews and the slave trade]]. No one who was in the room spoke about it for almost two years. Mallory and Bland deny that the offensive content in the conversation took place, but, according to ''[[Tablet Magazine]]'', \"multiple sources with knowledge of what happened confirmed the story.\"<ref>McSweeney, Leah and Jacob Siegel.  [https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/276694/is-the-womens-march-melting-down \"Is the Women's March Melting Down?\"] ''Tablet Magazine''.  10 December 2018.  12 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.thedailybeast.com/report-womens-march-leaders-made-anti-semitic-comments-to-fellow-founder Report: Women's March Leaders Made Anti-Semitic Comments to Fellow Founder], The Daily Beast, 11 December 2018</ref><ref name=\"StockmanAntiSemitism\">{{cite news |last1=Stockman |first1=Farah |title=Women's March Roiled by Accusations of Anti-Semitism |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/23/us/womens-march-anti-semitism.html?action=click&module=Top%20Stories&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=24 December 2018 |work=New York Times |date=23 December 2019}}</ref> Several journalists who shared the story were emailed by a [[Public relations|PR agency]] which claimed to be able to disprove the article, but would only share their information on condition of journalists keeping it off the record. Andrea Gonz\u00e1lez-Ram\u00edrez, a journalist from [[Refinery29]], claimed to have agreed to the PR firm's request, but the PR firm's fact checking failed to disprove Tablet Magazines claims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/12/womens-march-controversy-from-tablet-report-to-pr-email.html|title=What the Hell Is Going on With the Women's March?|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/pr-agency-for-womens-march-sends-terrible-email-to-every-reporter-on-twitter/|title=PR Agency For Women's March Sends Terrible Email to Every Reporter on Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefederalist.com/2018/12/12/check-incompetent-pr-response-expose-womens-marchs-anti-semitism/|title=Women's March Flack Sends Bizarre Email in Response To Tablet Expose|date=2018-12-12|website=The Federalist|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', opposition to and defiance of Trump infused the protests,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/women-march-protest-president-trump.html |title=Defiant Voices Flood U.S. Cities as Women Rally for Rights |last=Chira |first=Susan |date=January 21, 2017 |last2=Alcindor |first2=Yamiche |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122055946/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/women-march-protest-president-trump.html |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> which were sometimes directly called anti-Trump protests.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jan/22/the-guardian-view-on-the-anti-trump-marches-nasty-women-of-the-world-unite |title=The Guardian View on the anti-Trump marches: Nasty Women of the world unite |date=January 22, 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Editorial Board |issn=0261-3077|access-date=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122194035/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jan/22/the-guardian-view-on-the-anti-trump-marches-nasty-women-of-the-world-unite |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> Organizers stated that they were \"not targeting Trump specifically\" and that the event was \"more about being proactive about women's rights\". Sarsour called it \"a stand on social justice and human rights issues ranging from race, ethnicity, gender, religion, immigration and healthcare\".<ref name=\"The Guardian\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Heyboer |first1=Kelly |title=Women's March on Washington 2017: Who's going and when, how to get there and why it's happening |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2017/01/womens_march_washington_2017_dc_trump_when.html |work=The Star-Ledger |date=January 4, 2017 |accessdate=January 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912053046/http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2017/01/womens_march_washington_2017_dc_trump_when.html |archivedate=September 12, 2017 }}</ref> Wruble stated that \"it's about feminism [\u2026] But it's about more than that: It's about basic equality for all people.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/meet-the-women-of-the-womens-march-on-washington|title=These Are the Women Organizing the Women's March on Washington|work=Vogue|access-date=April 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Planned Parenthood]] partnered with the march by providing staff and offering knowledge related to planning a large-scale event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wtop.com/inauguration/2016/12/pair-longtime-activists-join-womens-march-washington|title=Pair of longtime activists join Women's March on Washington|last=Iannelli|first=Nick|date=December 29, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230090530/http://wtop.com/inauguration/2016/12/pair-longtime-activists-join-womens-march-washington/|archivedate=December 30, 2016|url-status=live|publisher=WTOP News|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> Planned Parenthood president [[Cecile Richards]] said that the march would \"send a strong message to the incoming administration that millions of people across this country are prepared to fight attacks on reproductive healthcare, abortion services and access to Planned Parenthood, [which] hopes that [in the future] many of the protesters will mobilize in its defense when Trump and congressional Republicans make their attempt to strip the organization of millions in federal funding\". The national organizing director stressed the importance of continuing action at a local level and remaining active after the event.<ref name=\"The Guardian\" />\n\n=== National co-chairs ===\n[[Vanessa Wruble]], co-founder, brought on Tamika D. Mallory, Carmen Perez and [[Linda Sarsour]] to serve as National Co-Chairs alongside [[Bob Bland]].<ref name=\"WMOW Explained\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/march-on-impeach-trump-vanessa-wruble|title=This Holiday Season, Give the Gift of Impeachment|work=Vogue|access-date=November 20, 2017|language=en}}</ref> The four co-chairs were Linda Sarsour, the executive director of the [[Arab American]] Association of New York; Tamika Mallory, a political organizer and former executive director of the [[National Action Network]]; Carmen Perez, an executive director of the political action group The Gathering for Justice; and Bob Bland, a fashion designer who focuses on ethical manufacturing.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/27/womens-march-on-washington-dc-guide |title=Women's March on Washington: a guide to the post-inaugural social justice event |last=Jamieson |first=Amber |date=December 27, 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227225001/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/27/womens-march-on-washington-dc-guide |archivedate=December 27, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Stein\">{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=Perry |last2=Somashekhar |first2=Sandhya |title=It started with a retiree. Now the Women's March could be the biggest inauguration demonstration |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/it-started-with-a-grandmother-in-hawaii-now-the-womens-march-on-washington-is-poised-to-be-the-biggest-inauguration-demonstration/2017/01/03/8af61686-c6e2-11e6-bf4b-2c064d32a4bf_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=January 3, 2017 |accessdate=January 4, 2017 |quote=Video of Bob Bland speaking about the rally. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104071254/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/it-started-with-a-grandmother-in-hawaii-now-the-womens-march-on-washington-is-poised-to-be-the-biggest-inauguration-demonstration/2017/01/03/8af61686-c6e2-11e6-bf4b-2c064d32a4bf_story.html |archivedate=January 4, 2017 }}</ref> [[Gloria Steinem]], [[Harry Belafonte]], [[LaDonna Harris]], [[Angela Davis]] and [[Dolores Huerta]] served as honorary co-chairs.<ref name=\"USA TODAY\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/05/womens-march-searches-themes-amid-concern-trump-gop-congress/96199000 |title=Women's march an 'entry point' for a new activist wave |last=Przybyla |first=Heidi |date=January 6, 2017 |newspaper=USA Today |accessdate=January 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107052351/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/05/womens-march-searches-themes-amid-concern-trump-gop-congress/96199000/ |archivedate=January 7, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.glamour.com/story/planned-parenthood-and-gloria-steinem-have-joined-the-womens-march-on-washington |title=Planned Parenthood and Gloria Steinem Have Joined the Women's March on Washington |last=Walker |first=Ashley Edwards |date=December 28, 2016 |work=Glamour|access-date=December 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229054641/http://www.glamour.com/story/planned-parenthood-and-gloria-steinem-have-joined-the-womens-march-on-washington |archivedate=December 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\nSeven women coordinated marches outside the U.S. The women were: Brit-Agnes Svaeri, Oslo, Norway;<ref>{{cite news |last1=De Jong |first1=Natasja |title=Demonstrations against Trump and for equality in Oslo |url=http://norwaytoday.info/news/demonstrations-trump-equality-oslo/ |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=Norway Today |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128092449/http://norwaytoday.info/news/demonstrations-trump-equality-oslo/ |archivedate=January 28, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hammerstrom |first1=Inger Lise |title=2000 deltok i internasjonal kvinnemarsj i Oslo |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/kvinner/2000-deltok-i-internasjonal-kvinnemarsj-i-oslo/a/23904137/ |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=VG |date=January 21, 2017 |language=Norwegian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202011428/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/kvinner/2000-deltok-i-internasjonal-kvinnemarsj-i-oslo/a/23904137/ |archivedate=February 2, 2017 }}Photo of Brit-Agnes Sv\u00e6ri</ref> Marissa McTasney, Toronto, Canada;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Loriggio |first1=Paolo |title=Canadian women to join Washington march on day after Trump's inauguration |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/12/31/canadian-woman-to-join-washington-march-on-day-after-trumps-inauguration.html |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=The Star (Toronto) |date=December 31, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422032912/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/12/31/canadian-woman-to-join-washington-march-on-day-after-trumps-inauguration.html |archivedate=April 22, 2017 }}</ref> Karen Olson, Geneva, Switzerland;<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands march in Geneva: 'We're hoping they're going to listen' |url=https://www.thelocal.ch/20170121/thousands-march-in-geneva-were-hoping-theyre-going-to-listen |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=The Local (Geneva) |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091700/https://www.thelocal.ch/20170121/thousands-march-in-geneva-were-hoping-theyre-going-to-listen |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }}</ref> Kerry Haggerty, London, United Kingdom;<ref name=\"empoweringuk\">{{cite news |title=Women Will March in the UK on First Day of Trump Presidency |url=http://empowering.hearst.co.uk/be-involved/women-will-march-in-the-uk-on-first-day-of-trump-presidency/ |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=Empowering Women |publisher=Hearst Magazines UK \u2013 The National Magazine Company Ltd |date=January 21, 2017 |quote=According to the Facebook page for the London march. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421093617/http://empowering.hearst.co.uk/be-involved/women-will-march-in-the-uk-on-first-day-of-trump-presidency/ |archivedate=April 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Rebecca Turnbow, Sydney, Australia;<ref>{{cite news |last1=De Bono |first1=Arielle |title=Women bring anti-Trump inauguration rallies to Australia |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/news-and-views/women-bring-antitrump-inauguration-rallies-to-australia-20170105-gtmtz7.html |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091912/http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/news-and-views/women-bring-antitrump-inauguration-rallies-to-australia-20170105-gtmtz7.html |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }}</ref> and Breanne Butler and Evvie Harmon in the United States.<ref name=\"huffpostglobal\">{{cite news |last1=Mayer |first1=Vivienne |title=How The Women's March on Washington Went Global |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/how-the-womens-march-on-washington-has-gone-global_us_586e342be4b021b75256f0f1 |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=HuffPost |date=January 23, 2017 |quote=[W]eekly Skype calls enabled all global organizers to update and support each other. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421093556/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/how-the-womens-march-on-washington-has-gone-global_us_586e342be4b021b75256f0f1 |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"voxnairobi\">{{cite news |last1=Wildman |first1=Sarah |title=The Women's March on Washington has spread to 60 countries around the globe |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/1/19/14316166/march-on-washington-women-global-solidarity |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |work=Vox |date=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421094436/http://www.vox.com/world/2017/1/19/14316166/march-on-washington-women-global-solidarity |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }} citing Facebook page used by the organizers in Nairobi, Kenya.</ref> The women organized the international marches through social media and had weekly Skype meetings to plot strategy.<ref name=\"huffpostglobal\"/><ref name=\"empoweringuk\"/><ref name=\"voxnairobi\"/>\n\n=== Policy platform ===\nOn January 12, the march organizers released a policy platform addressing [[reproductive rights]], immigration reform, healthcare reform, religious discrimination (primarily that against [[Islam in the United States|Muslim Americans]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/mission/ |title=Mission & Vision |publisher=Women's March on Washington |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123015852/https://www.womensmarch.com/mission/ |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref> [[LGBT rights|LGBTQ rights]], gender and racial inequities (primarily those that favor men and [[Non-Hispanic whites]], respectively), workers' rights, and other issues.<ref name=\"Cauterucci\">{{cite news |last1=Cauterucci |first1=Christina |title=The Women's March on Washington Has Released an Unapologetically Progressive Platform |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2017/01/12/the_women_s_march_on_washington_has_released_its_platform_and_it_is_unapologetically.html |work=Slate |date=January 12, 2017 |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113140714/http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2017/01/12/the_women_s_march_on_washington_has_released_its_platform_and_it_is_unapologetically.html |archivedate=January 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=Guiding>{{cite web |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/584086c7be6594762f5ec56e/t/5877e24a29687f9613e546ff/1484251725855/WMW+Guiding+Vision+%26+Definition+of+Principles.pdf |title=Guiding Vision and Definition of Principles |publisher=Women's March on Washington |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120013829/https://static1.squarespace.com/static/584086c7be6594762f5ec56e/t/5877e24a29687f9613e546ff/1484251725855/WMW+Guiding+Vision+%2526+Definition+of+Principles.pdf |archivedate=January 20, 2017 |access-date=January 13, 2017 }}</ref> \"Build bridges, not walls\" (a reference to Trump's [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier#Donald Trump|proposals for a border wall]]) became popular worldwide after the [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inaugural address]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Landsbaum |first1=Claire |title=This Global Protest Was Inspired by Donald Trump's Inauguration |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/trumps-inauguration-inspired-bridges-not-walls-protest.html |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=The Cut |agency=New York |date=January 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122225449/http://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/trumps-inauguration-inspired-bridges-not-walls-protest.html |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Aron |first1=Isabelle |title=Bridges Not Walls: anti-Trump protesters have dropped banners on London's bridges |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/bridges-not-walls-anti-trump-protesters-have-dropped-banners-on-londons-bridges-012017 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=Time Out London |date=January 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127191256/http://www.timeout.com/london/blog/bridges-not-walls-anti-trump-protesters-have-dropped-banners-on-londons-bridges-012017 |archivedate=January 27, 2017 }}</ref> and was a common refrain throughout the march.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Finnigan |first1=Lexi |title=Thousands of women march in UK cities on first full day of Trump presidency |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/21/thousands-women-prepare-march-uk-cities-first-day-trump-presidency/ |accessdate=January 25, 2016 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121101754/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/21/thousands-women-prepare-march-uk-cities-first-day-trump-presidency/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe organizers also addressed environmental issues: \"We believe that every person and every community in our nation has the right to clean water, clean air, and access to and enjoyment of public lands. We believe that our environment and our climate must be protected and that our land and natural resources cannot be exploited for corporate gain or greed\u2014especially at the risk of public safety and health.\"<ref name=Guiding />\n\n== Preparation and planning ==\n=== Name origin ===\n[[File:Women's March on Washington logo.png|thumb|Logo for the Women's March on Washington]]\n\nOriginally billed as the \"Million Women March,\" Wruble renamed the event<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2016/11/21/13651804/women-march-washington-trump-inauguration |title=The 'Women's March on Washington', explained |date=November 21, 2016|access-date=December 30, 2016 |publisher=Vox |author=Crockett, Emily |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103232129/http://www.vox.com/identities/2016/11/21/13651804/women-march-washington-trump-inauguration |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}</ref> to mirror the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]], the historic civil rights rally on the [[National Mall|Mall]] where [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] delivered his [[I Have a Dream|\"I Have a Dream\" speech]].<ref name=\"vogueprofile\">{{Cite news |last=Felsenthal |first=Julia |url=http://www.vogue.com/article/meet-the-women-of-the-womens-march-on-washington |title=These Are the Women Organizing the Women's March on Washington |work=Vogue |date=January 10, 2017|access-date=April 4, 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325212731/http://www.vogue.com/article/meet-the-women-of-the-womens-march-on-washington |archivedate=March 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news |author=Stein, Perry |title='Women's March on Washington' planning for big crowds on Inauguration weekend |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/11/14/womens-march-on-washington-planning-for-big-crowds-on-inauguration-weekend/ |work=The Washington Post |date=November 14, 2016|access-date=December 28, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229050457/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/11/14/womens-march-on-washington-planning-for-big-crowds-on-inauguration-weekend/ |archivedate=December 29, 2016 }}</ref> The rally also paid tribute to the 1997 [[Million Woman March]] in [[Philadelphia]], in which hundreds of thousands of African American women are said to have participated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tornquist |first1=Cynthia |title=Million Woman March fills Philadelphia streets |url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9710/25/million.woman.march2/index.html?_s=PM:US |publisher=CNN / Reuters |date=October 25, 1997 |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |quote=Organizers estimated that 2.1&nbsp;million people filled a mile-long avenue in early afternoon. Estimates made by police officers ranged from 300,000 to 1 million. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305094834/http://edition.cnn.com/US/9710/25/million.woman.march2/index.html?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=March 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Logistics planning ===\n[[File:DC National Guard Helps Provide Safety for Womens March on Washington.webm|thumb|right|DC National Guard providing security services during the Women's March on Washington]]\nBecause of scheduling conflicts at the Lincoln Memorial,<ref>{{cite news |author=Lang, Cady |title=Women's March on Washington Won't Be Happening at the Lincoln Memorial |url=http://time.com/4595399/women-march-washington-lincoln-memorial |work=Time |date=December 8, 2016|access-date=December 28, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230153211/http://time.com/4595399/women-march-washington-lincoln-memorial/ |archivedate=December 30, 2016 }}</ref> a permit was secured on December 9 to start the march on [[Independence Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Independence Avenue]] at the southwest corner of the [[United States Capitol|Capitol building]] and continue along the [[National Mall]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Stein, Perry |title=The Women's March on Washington says it has secured a starting location |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/12/09/the-womens-march-on-washington-says-they-have-secured-a-starting-location |work=The Washington Post |date=December 9, 2016 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224222849/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/12/09/the-womens-march-on-washington-says-they-have-secured-a-starting-location/ |archivedate=December 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBy January 20, 2017, 222,000 people had RSVP'd as going to the Washington, D.C., march and 251,000 had indicated interest.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felsenthal |first1=Julia |title=These Are the Women Organizing the Women's March on Washington |url=http://www.vogue.com/13520360/meet-the-women-of-the-womens-march-on-washington |date=January 10, 2017 |work=Vogue |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122172536/http://www.vogue.com/13520360/meet-the-women-of-the-womens-march-on-washington/ |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Blau |first1=Reuven |last2=Greene |first2=Leonard |title=Women's March on Washington could well outdraw the inauguration of President-elect Trump |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/women-march-washington-outdraw-trump-inauguration-article-1.2945187 |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=January 12, 2017 |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |quote=an estimated 200,000 women expected to participate. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114060516/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/women-march-washington-outdraw-trump-inauguration-article-1.2945187 |archivedate=January 14, 2017 }}</ref> On January 16, 2017, Fox News reported that authorities were expecting \"a crowd of almost 500,000 people\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Celebs to descend on Washington for anti-Trump mega-rally |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/01/16/celebs-to-descend-on-washington-for-anti-trump-mega-rally.html |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |date=January 16, 2017 |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116214351/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/01/16/celebs-to-descend-on-washington-for-anti-trump-mega-rally.html |archivedate=January 16, 2017 }}</ref> and the permit for the march issued by the [[National Park Service]] was revised by the head of D.C.'s Homeland Security department to half a million people<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-womens-march-live-organizers-up-their-crowd-estimate-for-1485012450-htmlstory.html |title=Women's marches live updates: Flagship Washington march gets underway |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |issn=0458-3035 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121232838/http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-womens-march-live-organizers-up-their-crowd-estimate-for-1485012450-htmlstory.html |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref>\u2014significantly more than the estimated attendance at President [[Donald Trump]]'s [[inauguration of Donald Trump|inauguration ceremony]] the previous day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nymag.com/selectall/2017/01/trumps-inauguration-looks-empty-compared-to-obama-2008.html |work=New York |title=Trump's Inauguration Looks Just Like Obama's, Only Without the Crowds |date=January 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122123552/http://nymag.com/selectall/2017/01/trumps-inauguration-looks-empty-compared-to-obama-2008.html |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/22/trump-inauguration-crowd-sean-spicers-claims-versus-the-evidence |work=The Guardian |title=Trump's inauguration crowd: Sean Spicer's claims versus the evidence |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122062210/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/22/trump-inauguration-crowd-sean-spicers-claims-versus-the-evidence |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Partnerships ===\nIn late December, organizers announced that over 100 organizations would provide assistance during the march and support the event across their social media platforms.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2016/12/19/amnesty_international_usa_signs_on_as_women_s_march_partner.html |title=Amnesty International USA Signs on as Women's March Partner |last=Cauterucci |first=Christina |date=December 19, 2016 |work=Slate |issn=1091-2339|access-date=January 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102204623/http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2016/12/19/amnesty_international_usa_signs_on_as_women_s_march_partner.html |archivedate=January 2, 2017 }}</ref> By January 18, more than 400 organizations were listed as \"partners\" on the March's official website.<ref name=\"Partners\">{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/partners |title=Partners |publisher=Women's March on Washington |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102081858/https://www.womensmarch.com/partners/ |archivedate=January 2, 2017 |access-date=January 1, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"Bernstein\">Bernstein, Leandra (January 18, 2017). [http://komonews.com/news/nation-world/more-pro-life-groups-removed-as-partners-of-the-womens-march More pro-life groups removed as official partners of the Women's March] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120193202/http://komonews.com/news/nation-world/more-pro-life-groups-removed-as-partners-of-the-womens-march |date=January 20, 2017 }}, KOMO News/[[Sinclair Broadcasting Group]]. Retrieved January 18, 2017.</ref>\n\n[[Planned Parenthood]] (which has received federal funding since 1970, when President Richard Nixon signed into law the [[Family Planning Services and Population Research Act]]) and the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] were listed as the two \"premier partners\".<ref name=\"Partners\" /> Other organizations listed as partners included the [[AFL\u2013CIO]], [[Amnesty International USA]], the [[Mothers of the Movement]], the [[National Center for Lesbian Rights]], the [[National Organization for Women]], [[MoveOn.org]], [[Human Rights Watch]], [[Code Pink]], [[Black Girls Rock!]], the [[NAACP]], the [[American Indian Movement]], [[Emily's List]], [[Oxfam]], [[Greenpeace USA]], and the [[League of Women Voters]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"Partners\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2016/12/amnesty-int-usa-partners-with-womens-march-on-washington.html |title=The Women's March on Washington Has a New Sponsor |last=Ryan |first=Lisa |date=December 20, 2016 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=January 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104163953/http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/12/amnesty-int-usa-partners-with-womens-march-on-washington.html |archivedate=January 4, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/12/us/politics/womens-march-bikers-trump.html |title=Women's March and Bikers for Trump Claim Inaugural Demonstration Spots |last=Rogers |first=Katie |date=December 12, 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213190654/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/12/us/politics/womens-march-bikers-trump.html |archivedate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-to-get-involved-with-womens-march-on-washington |title=Here's How YOU Can Get Involved With the Women's March on Washington |last=Dwyer |first=Kate |date=December 30, 2016 |work=Teen Vogue|access-date=January 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103123737/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-to-get-involved-with-womens-march-on-washington |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:2017 Women's March California.jpg|thumb|Members of the [[League of Women Voters|Leagues of Women Voters]] participating in Women's March]]\nOn January 13, event organizers granted the [[anti-abortion feminism|anti-abortion feminist]] group [[New Wave Feminists]] partnership status. But after the organization's involvement was publicized in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', it was removed from the partners page on the march's website.<ref>Green, Emma (January 16, 2017). [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/pro-lifers-womens-march/513104 \"These Pro-Lifers Are Headed to the Women's March on Washington: Is there room in the movement for people who morally object to abortion?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119082804/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/pro-lifers-womens-march/513104/ |date=January 19, 2017 }}, ''The Atlantic''. Retrieved January 22, 2017.</ref> Other anti-abortion groups that had been granted partnership status, including [[Abby Johnson (activist)|Abby Johnson]]'s And Then There Were None (ATTWN) and Stanton Healthcare, were subsequently unlisted as partners as well. New Wave Feminists and Johnson still participated in the official march, alongside other anti-abortion groups such as ATTWN, [[Students for Life of America]], and ''Life Matters Journal''.{{efn|name=CatholicNews1|\"No one contacted them to give them the news, she said, but they found out after a flurry of stories announced pro-life groups like hers were taken off the roster as partners by officials. The groups And Then There Were None and Students for Life of America also were denied or taken off the Women's March roster. 'We don't want to be opposing the (Women's March),' Herndon-De La Rosa said. 'We're not trying to make them look bad.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guidos |first1=Rhina |title=Though snubbed by Women's March, pro-life groups will still participate |url=http://www.catholicnews.com/services/englishnews/2017/though-snubbed-by-womens-march-prolife-groups-will-still-participate.cfm |work=Catholic News |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.fo/20170123074126/http://www.catholicnews.com/services/englishnews/2017/though-snubbed-by-womens-march-prolife-groups-will-still-participate.cfm |archivedate=January 23, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n== Participation ==\n[[File:Women's March White House 2017b.jpg|thumb|The Women's March near the [[White House]]]]\nWhile organizers had originally expected over 200,000 people,<ref name=\"Wallace\">{{cite news |title=Crowd Scientists Say Women's March in Washington Had 3 Times as Many People as Trump's Inauguration |last1=Wallace |first1=Tim |last2=Parlapiano |first2=Alicia |date=January 22, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/22/us/politics/womens-march-trump-crowd-estimates.html |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313210125/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/22/us/politics/womens-march-trump-crowd-estimates.html |archivedate=March 13, 2017 }}</ref> the march ended up drawing between 440,000<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/23/511267138/politics-aside-counting-crowds-is-tricky |title=Politics Aside, Counting Crowds Is Tricky |author=Jon Hamilton |date=January 23, 2017 |publisher=NPR |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127183529/http://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/23/511267138/politics-aside-counting-crowds-is-tricky |archivedate=January 27, 2017 }}</ref> to 500,000 in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"WashPost3\">{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=Perry |last2=Hendrix |first2=Steve |last3=Hauslohner |first3=Abigail |title=Women's marches: More than one million protesters vow to resist President Trump |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/womens-march-on-washington-a-sea-of-pink-hatted-protesters-vow-to-resist-donald-trump/2017/01/21/ae4def62-dfdf-11e6-acdf-14da832ae861_story.html?hpid=hp_hp-bignews2_banner-hed%3Ahomepage%2Fstory |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015120609/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/womens-march-on-washington-a-sea-of-pink-hatted-protesters-vow-to-resist-donald-trump/2017/01/21/ae4def62-dfdf-11e6-acdf-14da832ae861_story.html?hpid=hp_hp-bignews2_banner-hed%3Ahomepage%2Fstory |archivedate=October 15, 2017 }}</ref> The [[Washington Metro]] system had its second-busiest day ever with over a million trips taken, considerably larger than the inauguration day's ridership and second only to the [[first inauguration of Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://washington.cbslocal.com/2017/01/24/womens-march-second-highest-day-ever-for-metro-ridership/ |title=Women's March Second Highest Day Ever for Metro Ridership |access-date=January 30, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202064311/http://washington.cbslocal.com/2017/01/24/womens-march-second-highest-day-ever-for-metro-ridership/ |archivedate=February 2, 2017 }}</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that crowd-scientists estimate that the Women's March was three times the size of the Trump inauguration, which they estimate at 160,000 attendees.<ref name=\"Wallace\" /> However, ''The Washington Post'' and ''The New York Times'' have stated that it is difficult to accurately calculate crowd size<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/01/22/its-usually-difficult-for-people-to-agree-on-a-crowds-size-heres-why/ |title=It's usually difficult for people to agree on a crowd's size. Here's why |author=Amy B. Wang |date=January 22, 2017 |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125152545/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/01/22/its-usually-difficult-for-people-to-agree-on-a-crowds-size-heres-why/ |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/20/us/politics/trump-inauguration-crowd.html |title=Trump's Inauguration vs. Obama's: Comparing the Crowds |author1=Tim Wallace |author2=Karen Yourish |author3=Troy Griggs |date=January 20, 2017 |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127014105/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/20/us/politics/trump-inauguration-crowd.html |archivedate=January 27, 2017 }}</ref> and other estimates of the Trump inauguration range from 250,000 to 600,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/jan/21/sean-spicer/trump-had-biggest-inaugural-crowd-ever-metrics-don |title=Donald Trump had biggest inaugural crowd ever? Metrics don't show it |author=Linda Qiu |date=January 21, 2017 |website=Politifact |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126175257/http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/jan/21/sean-spicer/trump-had-biggest-inaugural-crowd-ever-metrics-don/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/1/21/14347298/trump-inauguration-crowd-size |title=Trump claims 1.5&nbsp;million people came to his inauguration. Here's what the evidence shows |author=Timothy Lee |date=January 23, 2017 |website=VOX |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125190524/http://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/1/21/14347298/trump-inauguration-crowd-size |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 3,300,000 \u2013 4,600,000 people participated in the United States<ref name=\"Atlantic exhausting work\" /> and up to 5 million did worldwide.<ref name=\"auto27\" /><ref name=\"auto8\" /><ref name=\"auto9\" />\n\nPacked cars, buses, airplanes, and trains commuted protesters to the march. The large crowds enabled Washington's Subway to break 1,000,000 passengers for only the second time in its history. The 1,001,613 trips are the second busiest day, the highest counted total (as the highest, from Obama's First Inauguration is only an estimate) and the highest single-day ridership for a weekend day breaking the previous record of 825,437 trips set during the [[Rally to Restore Sanity and/or Fear]].\n\n=== Washington, D.C. ===\n\n==== Speakers ====\n[[File:Scarlett Johansson at Women's March on Washington (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Scarlett Johansson]] at Women's March on Washington]]\n\nThe official list of speakers included [[America Ferrera]],<ref name=\"ew20170109\">{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Danielle |title=America Ferrera, Madonna, Chelsea Handler, Katy Perry, more to participate in Women's March on Washington |url=https://ew.com/news/2017/01/09/womens-march-washington-america-ferrera-katy-perry |accessdate=January 10, 2017 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=January 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110101401/http://ew.com/news/2017/01/09/womens-march-washington-america-ferrera-katy-perry/ |archivedate=January 10, 2017 }}</ref> [[Scarlett Johansson]], and [[Gloria Steinem]]. Other speakers were [[Sophie Cruz]], [[Angela Davis]], and [[Michael Moore]], as well as [[Cecile Richards]], [[Ilyasah Shabazz]], [[Janet Mock]], [[LaDonna Harris]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], [[Maryum Ali]], Rabbi [[Sharon Brous]], Sister [[Simone Campbell]], [[Ashley Judd]], [[Melissa Harris-Perry]], [[Randi Weingarten]], [[Van Jones]], [[Kristin Rowe-Finkbeiner]], [[Roslyn Brock]], Mayor [[Muriel Bowser]], Senators [[Tammy Duckworth]] (D-IL) and [[Kamala Harris]] (D-CA), [[Donna Hylton]], [[Ai-jen Poo]], and [[Raquel Willis]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Landsbaum |first=Claire |date=January 18, 2017 |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/here-are-all-the-speakers-at-the-womens-march-on-washington.html |title=Here's the Official List of Speakers for the Women's March on Washington |work=New York |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119070747/http://nymag.com/thecut/2017/01/here-are-all-the-speakers-at-the-womens-march-on-washington.html |archivedate=January 19, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Speakers |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/speakers/ |website=Women's March on Washington |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128154838/https://www.womensmarch.com/speakers/ |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |access-date=April 30, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/senator-tammy-duckworth-womens-march-on-washington-411423165.html |title=Sen. Duckworth Delivers Impassioned Speech at Women's March |publisher=NBC Chicago |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125150444/http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/senator-tammy-duckworth-womens-march-on-washington-411423165.html |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-womens-march-live-california-sen-kamala-harris-strikes-a-1485021491-htmlstory.html |title=Women's marches live updates: Millions march in L.A. and around the world following Trump's inauguration |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |last=Wesfall |first=Julie |date=January 22, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121193835/http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-womens-march-live-california-sen-kamala-harris-strikes-a-1485021491-htmlstory.html |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"cspan-21jan2017\">{{cite news |title=Women's March on Washington |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?422332-1/womens-march-washington-protests-new-trump-administration |accessdate=September 19, 2017 |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920045835/https://www.c-span.org/video/?422332-1%2Fwomens-march-washington-protests-new-trump-administration |archivedate=September 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSteinem commented \"Our constitution does not begin with 'I, the President.' It begins with, 'We, the People.' I am proud to be one of thousands who have come to Washington to make clear that we will keep working for a democracy in which we are linked as human beings, not ranked by race or gender or class or any other label.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/>\n\nFerrera stated, \"If we \u2013 the millions of Americans who believe in common decency, in the greater good, in justice for all \u2013 if we fall into the trap by separating ourselves by our causes and our labels, then we will weaken our fight and we will lose. But if we commit to what aligns us, if we stand together steadfast and determined, then we stand a chance of saving the soul of our country.\"<ref name=\"ABC 10 empowering\">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/10-empowering-quotes-womens-march-washington/story?id=44948631 |title=10 Empowering Quotes from Women's March on Washington |first=Joi-Marie |last=McKenzie |date=January 21, 2017 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121232335/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/10-empowering-quotes-womens-march-washington/story?id=44948631 |archivedate=January 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nJohansson called for long-term change: \"Once the heaviness [of the election] began to subside, an opportunity has presented itself to make real long-term change, not just for future Americans, but in the way we view our responsibility to get involved with and stay active in our communities. Let this weight not drag you down, but help to get your heels stuck in.\"<ref name=\"ABC 10 empowering\"/>\n\nThe youngest presenter at the Washington D.C. march, 6-year-old [[Sophie Cruz]], said, \"Let us fight with love, faith, and courage so that our families will not be destroyed,\" and ended her speech saying, \"I also want to tell the children not to be afraid, because we are not alone. There are still many people that have their hearts filled with love. Let's keep together and fight for the rights. God is with us.\" Cruz repeated her speech in Spanish.<ref name=\"The Huffington Post\">{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sophie-cruz_us_58839698e4b096b4a23201f6 |title=Watch 6-Year-Old Sophie Cruz Give One of the Best Speeches of the Women's March |last=Blay |first=Zeba |work=HuffPost |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123195052/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sophie-cruz_us_58839698e4b096b4a23201f6 |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}Sophie Cruz speaks at the Woman's March</ref>\n\n[[File:Women's March - Washington DC 2017 (31771083973).jpg|thumb|[[Angela Davis]] at Women's March on Washington]]\n\n[[Alicia Keys]] performed at the rally saying, \"We are mothers. We are caregivers. We are artists. We are activists. We are entrepreneurs, doctors, leaders of industry and technology. Our potential is unlimited. We rise.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post 20170121\">{{cite web |title=Celebrities join the throngs at the Washington Women's March |website=The Washington Post |date=January 21, 2017 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2017/01/21/celebrities-join-the-throngs-at-the-washington-womens-march |last=Heil |first=Emily |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123052106/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2017/01/21/celebrities-join-the-throngs-at-the-washington-womens-march/ |archivedate=January 23, 2017 }}</ref> [[Angela Davis]] said, \"We recognize that we are collective agents of history and that history cannot be deleted like web pages.\" [[Muhammad Ali#Marriages and children|Maryum Ali]] also spoke, saying, \"Don't get frustrated, get involved. Don't complain, organize.\"<ref name=\"ABC 10 empowering\"/>\n\n=== Other U.S. locations ===\n{{Main|List of 2017 Women's March locations}}\n{{See also|Women's March on Portland}}\n\nAcross the United States, there were a total of 408 planned marches.<ref name=\"auto27\" />\n\n=== International ===\n{{Main|List of 2017 Women's March locations}}\n\nMarches occurred worldwide, with 198 in 84 other countries.<ref name=\"auto27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.womensmarch.com/sisters |title=Sister Marches |publisher=Women's March on Washington |accessdate=January 23, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123010344/https://www.womensmarch.com/sisters |archivedate=January 23, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\"/> Organisers of the event reported 673 marches worldwide, including 20 in Mexico and 29 in Canada.<ref name=\"FT 100,000\"/> Women in India also organized a nationwide march on January 21, 2017 called [[I Will Go Out]] to demand access to safe public spaces. It was held in small countries such as Belgium, Costa Rica, Latvia.<ref name=\"womensmarchglobal.com\">\"Look Back, March Forward.\" Women's March Global, January 21, 2018, http://www.womensmarchglobal.com/look-back-march-forward/.</ref> The movement also took place in countries in Africa, including Kenya, Nigeria, and Tanzania all held marches calling for women to have equal rights, and specifically demanding an end to violence against women.<ref name=\"womensmarchglobal.com\"/>\n\n=== Participation by well-known people ===\n\n==== Political figures ====\n[[File:Atlanta Womens March John Lewis.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] at the Atlanta Women's March]]\nU.S. Senator [[Cory Booker]], former [[U.S. Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]], and civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]] attended the Washington march.<ref>Moriah Balingit and Victoria St. Martin, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/2017/live-updates/politics/womens-march-on-washington/cory-booker-john-kerry-on-scene/ Cory Booker, John Kerry on scene] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302132422/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/2017/live-updates/politics/womens-march-on-washington/cory-booker-john-kerry-on-scene/ |date=March 2, 2017 }}, ''The Washington Post'' (January 21, 2017).</ref><ref>Katie Reilly, [http://time.com/4642365/john-kerry-womens-march/ John Kerry Joins Women's March on Washington While Walking His Dog] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228195558/http://time.com/4642365/john-kerry-womens-march/ |date=February 28, 2017 }}, ''Time'' (January 21, 2017).</ref><ref name=\"elle20170121\"/> [[Anne-Marie Slaughter]], president of New America and former [[Director of Policy Planning]] at the [[U.S. State Department]], attended the New York City march.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/8dd850d2-df27-11e6-86ac-f253db7791c6 |title=Why millions of women, girls and men felt compelled to march |last=Slaughter |first=Anne-Marie |date=January 22, 2017 |work=Financial Times |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122050738/https://www.ft.com/content/8dd850d2-df27-11e6-86ac-f253db7791c6 |archivedate=January 22, 2017 }}</ref> [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] attended the Atlanta rally, which saw more than 60,000 march to the [[Georgia State Capitol]].<ref>Darnell, Tim (January 21, 2017). [http://www.11alive.com/news/politics/60000-plus-jam-downtown-atlanta-for-womens-march/389625626 60,000-plus jam downtown Atlanta for women's march], 11alive.com' retrieved January 21, 2017.</ref>\n\nSenator [[Bernie Sanders]] of Vermont delivered a speech at the march in [[Montpelier, Vermont|Montpelier]] in front of the [[Vermont State House]], as did other Vermont political figures, such as former Governor [[Madeleine Kunin]] and current Lieutenant Governor [[David Zuckerman (politician)|David Zuckerman]].<ref>Annie Russell, [http://digital.vpr.net/post/15000-rally-montpelier-womens-march-forcing-i-89-exit-closures#stream/0 15,000 Rally In Montpelier For Women's March, Forcing I-89 Exit Closures] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130043617/http://digital.vpr.net/post/15000-rally-montpelier-womens-march-forcing-i-89-exit-closures |date=January 30, 2017 }}, [[Vermont Public Radio]] (January 21, 2017).</ref> Both Massachusetts Senators [[Elizabeth Warren]] and [[Ed Markey]] participated in the Boston Women's March,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Colin Dwyer |author2=Maggie Penman |author3=Mandalit del Barco |author4=Frank Langfitt |date=January 21, 2017 |title=Women's Marches Go Global: Postcards From Protests Around The World |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/21/510940708/womens-march-on-washington-goes-worldwide-snapshots-from-around-the-globe |work=NPR |access-date=February 25, 2019}}</ref> along with Mayor [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]].\n\n[[Jacinda Ardern]], Prime Minister of New Zealand since October 2017, gave a speech after marching in [[Auckland, New Zealand|Auckland]]; New Zealand was chronologically the first country in the world to participate in the march.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roy|first1=Eleanor Ainge|title=Jacinda Ardern retorts to Donald Trump: 'No one marched when I was elected'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/nov/17/jacinda-ardern-to-donald-trump-no-one-marched-when-i-was-elected|accessdate=November 18, 2017|work=The Guardian (UK)|date=November 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11786381 |title=New Zealanders march for women's rights in wake of Donald Trump's inauguration |work=[[New Zealand Herald]] |date=January 21, 2017 |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Additional celebrity participation ====\nIn Washington, DC:<ref name=\"elle20170121\">{{cite web |first1=Megan |last1=Friedman |first2=Lyndsey |last2=Matthews |title=Celebrity Sightings at the Women's March on Washington \u2013 Celebs at Million Woman March |website=ELLE |date=January 21, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/news/g29350/womens-march-washington-celebrities |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125011139/http://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/news/g29350/womens-march-washington-celebrities/ |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=CBSNewscelebsattend>{{cite news |title=Celebrities attend Women's Marches around the world (Photos) |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/celebrities-attend-womens-marches-around-the-world/4/ |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129194044/http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/celebrities-attend-womens-marches-around-the-world/4/ |archivedate=January 29, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"Izadi 201701\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/01/23/plenty-of-celebrities-showed-up-for-the-womens-marches-as-demonstrators-not-performers |title=Plenty of celebrities showed up for the women's marches \u2013 as demonstrators, not performers |first=Elahe |last=Izadi |date=January 23, 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126033644/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/01/23/plenty-of-celebrities-showed-up-for-the-womens-marches-as-demonstrators-not-performers/ |archivedate=January 26, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"newsweekcelebsattend\">{{cite news |last1=Loffredo |first1=Nicholas |title=Women's March: Samantha Bee, Chelsea Handler Among Celebs in Solidarity |url=http://www.newsweek.com/samantha-bee-chelsea-handler-womens-march-546002 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=Newsweek |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125030715/http://www.newsweek.com/samantha-bee-chelsea-handler-womens-march-546002 |archivedate=January 25, 2017 }}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=15em}}\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD MORE PEOPLE TO THIS LIST. IT IS SUPPOSED TO BE REPRESENTATIVE, NOT EXHAUSTIVE.